A few practical approaches, from least to most effort:

1. Manual research (highest quality)
• Search "local news [city] RSS" or "[publication] RSS feed"
• Regional press associations often maintain directories (e.g. Regional Media Australia, News Media Canada)
• Wikipedia's "newspapers in [state/country]" pages are a good starting point for finding publication names, then you check if they have feeds

2. OPML directories (ready-made lists)
• Sites like Feedspot, AllTop, and NewsBlur maintain categorised feed directories
• You can scrape these for domain names to add to SEEDS
• Quality varies — many are stale

3. Google search patterns
• site:*.com​.au inurl:"/feed" finds Australian WordPress sites with feeds
• "rss​.xml" "local news" [city] surfaces feeds directly
• These can be batch-processed to extract domains

4. Existing RSS aggregators
• Inoreader, Feedly, and NewsBlur all have public "popular feeds by category/region" pages
• These are pre-vetted and actively read, so higher quality signal
